00:14:51.170 --> 00:14:54.010
to fix any accessibility issues.

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:57.250
So that's why I would
recommend WordPress.

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:59.640
Not just because they
wanted me to speak,

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:04.600
but because they actually are
advocating what they preach.

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:07.010
So yes, what guidance is available?

00:15:08.550 --> 00:15:10.690
That also can just be a help file.

00:15:10.690 --> 00:15:13.690
Like if I want to know
how to do something,

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:19.160
if I can't easily find the
answer, that's a no-no.

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:22.310
I want to know how
to do things myself,

00:15:22.310 --> 00:15:25.760
and if I can't find the answer
easily and it's not intuitive,

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:26.910
it's something to avoid then.

00:15:28.390 --> 00:15:29.760
And yes, I keep mentioning it,

00:15:29.761 --> 00:15:31.770
can alternative text
be added to an image?

00:15:33.680 --> 00:15:38.630
I did have experience
with an authoring tool

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:42.240
where it had a banner image,
and you were not allowed

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:45.130
to add any alternative text .

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:48.970
And people kept putting a lot
of meaningful images in there

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:50.080
with no description.

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:51.700
And I said the only
way to work around it,

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:53.700
because I didn't have the
choice, I wasn't allowed

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:56.010
to choose the plugins or
the tool that we were using.

00:15:57.550 --> 00:16:01.570
So what I was doing was
adding a caption to the image,

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:04.510
because it was the only
thing I could think

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:09.060
of that would give a text
alternative to the image.

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:10.970
It was a hack, it wasn't pretty.

00:16:13.010 --> 00:16:18.480
And I do think when it
comes to these hacks,

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:23.260
they're a well-meaning way around
things, but they shouldn't be needed.

00:16:27.570 --> 00:16:30.480
Our links start using
more than color and line.

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:36.800
This is another one, that sometimes
a bold link is not enough for me.

00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:38.320
I prefer to have an underline.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:39.200
I'm old school.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:43.540
If I see a change of color and
an underline, I know it's a link.

00:16:43.540 --> 00:16:47.210
But bold text is a
slight differentiator.

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:54.940
But yes, if they style the links
and you can't change the format

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:58.260
to suit your preferences, you
have to make it easy for the users

00:16:58.260 --> 00:17:00.900
to understand,
that's another one to be aware of.

00:17:03.050 --> 00:17:05.760
Can the keyboard focus
all actionable items?

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:06.360
Yes.

00:17:06.360 --> 00:17:10.590
Do they have div items where
they add in items for you?

00:17:10.590 --> 00:17:12.430
Again, going back to
the snake oil people.

00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:19.410
If they add in lots of divs or
nested divs... It can be done

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:24.650
due to JavaScript being injected
in, like when using React kind

00:17:24.650 --> 00:17:29.450
of frameworks where embed
divs into links that means

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:32.560
that the list items are no longer
recognised by the screen reader.

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:37.520
But it can also make things
like buttons not be a button.

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:39.130
The keyboard can't focus it.

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:43.980
And also another
one to add to that.

00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:46.500
If it's focused,
can I see the focus?

00:17:48.250 --> 00:17:50.290
So is it focusable and
can I see the focus?

00:17:50.290 --> 00:17:51.760
That's a good one to be checking.

00:17:53.170 --> 00:17:57.930
And if you copy accessible content
in, like if you find an image

00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:01.600
with a brilliant alternative
text and I copy and paste it,

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:04.150
does the alternative text get
moved over too, or do I have

00:18:04.150 --> 00:18:07.950
to copy and paste the alternative
text into my image after I've copied

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:08.950
and pasted it?

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:15.020
I know that sounds like
something that's a minor thing,

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:19.150
but if you're doing large
amounts of content creation,

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:23.750
that can be an RSI sort of a passive
strain injury sort of incident.

00:18:23.750 --> 00:18:29.900
So that is for your ease of
not having to do an extra step

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:31.320
to get the accessibility embedded.

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:43.390
So, part A. Part A of ATAG is about,
is the tool itself accessible to use?

00:18:44.850 --> 00:18:49.610
So this is important if as part
of your content creation team,

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:52.720
you've got anyone that might
rely on assistive technology

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:57.360
or use assistive technology
on a daily basis.

00:18:57.360 --> 00:19:02.440
So, I always judge it,
could I understand this

00:19:02.440 --> 00:19:04.390
if I haven't had my coffee?

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:10.220
But for part A, we have A1,
the authoring tool user interface

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:12.620
follows applicable
accessibility guidelines.

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:19.360
In other words, if it's web
based, does it follow WCAG?

00:19:19.360 --> 00:19:22.810
Does it meet the WCAG
checkpoints, Yes or no?

00:19:22.810 --> 00:19:26.400
That one is the largest part
of an ATAG world, making sure

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.490
that WCAG is covered.

00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:30.609
But it also applies...

00:19:30.610 --> 00:19:35.520
It has a section for non
web based functionality.

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:40.360
So if you have an application,
it's a similar principle of WCAG,

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:42.350
but it is a stand-alone
application.

00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:46.770
So it's not HTML based, basically.

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:48.890
It's making sure buttons
announces buttons.

00:19:48.890 --> 00:19:50.990
When you fix them,
do they interact with the keyboard?

00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:51.990
Same sort of thing.

00:19:52.660 --> 00:19:56.040
If I'm using a tool,
can I use it using a screen reader?

00:19:56.040 --> 00:19:57.730
Can I use it with a keyboard alone?

00:19:57.730 --> 00:19:59.790
Can I zoom in?

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:01.290
Can I change the colors?

00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:04.900
Are the colors easy to
see in the first place?

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:06.910
Am I allowed to change?

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:12.130
Those are all things that should be
part of checking if it's accessible.

00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:17.020
Then again, editing views,
are they perceivable?

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:25.020
So if I'm editing content, am I able
to get into all the different items?

00:20:25.310 --> 00:20:28.200
Do I understand what
I'm putting in where?

00:20:30.370 --> 00:20:35.260
So you need to make sure that there
is alternative content available

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:37.330
to authors as needed.

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:40.130
For instance, if it's a drag and
drop, can the keyboard do it?

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.340
And just needs to be
programmatically determined.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:48.200
And then are they operable?

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:50.750
You've got Paul coming in here.

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:52.510
So editing views,
are they operable?

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:53.780
Can I use a keyboard?

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:55.050
Do I have to use a mouse?

00:20:55.050 --> 00:21:01.460
Can I use another tool to edit
items in the editing view?

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:04.730
And are they understandable?

00:21:04.730 --> 00:21:07.710
Again, is the language simple?

00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:13.920
And does it make sense with
the roles assigned and so on?

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:17.510
Because they don't have robust.

00:21:17.510 --> 00:21:24.270
Because basically when it comes
to editing views, we have ATAG

00:21:24.270 --> 00:21:26.960
at a glance, which I think
is a very good starting point

00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:30.570
for anyone when it comes
to these guidelines.

00:21:30.570 --> 00:21:31.590
But we don't have robust.

00:21:31.590 --> 00:21:35.490
Because robust is for content
you are creating yourself.

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:40.760
This is more about checking the
tool is doing as it needs to.

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:44.630
And as we all know,
4.1.1 [Inaudible 21:42]

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:47.060
is no longer tested.

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:52.180
Well, no longer deemed worthwhile
to be tested, I should say.

00:21:54.730 --> 00:21:56.080
But still I'm excited.

00:21:56.080 --> 00:21:59.490
4.1.1 one was always
a bit of a long winded

00:21:59.490 --> 00:22:02.180
with very low severity
issues type of checkpoints.

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:03.580
So anyway.

00:22:03.580 --> 00:22:07.020
But robust is not there
because these are things

00:22:07.020 --> 00:22:15.020
that are covered partly by
WCAG and the editing views.

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:17.840
You're not checking that
they've been built correctly.

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:22.040
You're just making sure that the
user has no issues with interacting

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:23.040
with them.

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:29.260
Anyway, part B. This is a
bit that's most important for

00:22:29.260 --> 00:22:33.130
when you choose a plugin;
making sure it supports you in

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:35.480
being able to produce
accessible content.

00:22:37.160 --> 00:22:45.000
So we have part B of B1:
fully automatic process

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.830
produce accessible content.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:51.170
This is not doing the job for you
people, it's not the overlay thing,

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:56.120
it's more about does it have a
wizard that identifies where you need

00:22:56.120 --> 00:22:57.340
to change things?

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:02.900
Does it flag things going, Oh
my word, you can't publish this,

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:05.140
you haven't added an alt tag.

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:06.930
I'm not saying it should
have an alarm like that

00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:08.390
but it would be kind
of cool if it did,

00:23:08.390 --> 00:23:12.250
because I know I personally sometimes
forget or I get a bit rushed,

00:23:12.250 --> 00:23:16.310
and it would be really
nice if there was a warning

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:18.600
that sometimes it
needs to be checked.

00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:24.240
I know that on Word it will
have a little icon at the bottom

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:26.840
to let me know that there's
issues with the accessibility.

00:23:28.390 --> 00:23:36.390
So is there something that will
help do some of the grunt work,

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:41.040
I call it, checking everything
for you to make sure that there...

00:23:42.310 --> 00:23:45.570
It doesn't do all the work
because it doesn't make sure that,

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:48.170
say, the alternative
text is meaningful.

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:53.680
It's more about checking, are the
programmatic items there, yes or no?

00:23:56.440 --> 00:24:02.050
And B2, to complement B1, as I said
before, it needs to have processes

00:24:02.050 --> 00:24:06.050
to help you produce content,
but B2s are author supported

00:24:06.050 --> 00:24:07.550
in making accessible content.

00:24:07.550 --> 00:24:10.710
It's not doing it for
you, it's supporting.

00:24:10.710 --> 00:24:13.690
So it's making sure that
it gives you guides.

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:17.470
It will assist you with
templates that are accessible,

00:24:17.470 --> 00:24:21.460
and I know WordPress again,
has a lot of accessible contents

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:23.790
and templates.

00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:26.020
Don't always believe it,
just because it says it is.

00:24:26.020 --> 00:24:30.390
I always recommend quickly checking
them out, because as we all know,

00:24:30.390 --> 00:24:35.900
I could say that I was German,
for instance, but with my accent,

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:39.310
you might be like, I'm not sure
you're telling the truth Helen.

00:24:39.310 --> 00:24:41.440
So just because I say
something does make it true.

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:44.330
So just because something says
it's accessible, doesn't mean it

00:24:44.330 --> 00:24:45.820
might be 100%.

00:24:45.820 --> 00:24:50.680
So yes, it's great that they produce
accessible content and templates,

00:24:52.440 --> 00:24:55.910
but also you need to make sure
that you can change templates

00:24:55.910 --> 00:24:59.240
to suit your needs and to suit
your audience's needs as needed.

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:05.070
And also, will they help authors
with accessible pre-authored content?

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:09.200
Again, that's helping
with making sure that

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:13.940
if you are a little bit non
techy, some of this will seem

00:25:13.940 --> 00:25:16.610
a little bit much to start up with.

00:25:16.610 --> 00:25:20.400
So I recommend if you've got
a great support community

00:25:21.470 --> 00:25:24.490
that will help,
that makes a massive difference

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:27.070
to helping create
accessible content.

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:32.010
And yes, are authors supported
in improving accessibility.

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:36.460
So again, it's a bit like
the wizard part of it again.

00:25:36.460 --> 00:25:40.760
When I say wizard, it's not the
paperclip, but pretty much like.

00:25:42.010 --> 00:25:46.480
And it's basically sometimes
when I'm not sure going

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:50.270
through the accessibility options,
I might not be able to get

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:52.600
to the reordering of content.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:55.380
Like on slides,
sometimes it goes forward,

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:57.980
sometimes it goes backwards
with the readability.

00:25:57.980 --> 00:26:00.040
It all depends on what
my first slide did.

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:06.270
And then I get an option to
click, to go to the reorder option

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:09.350
because I find it easily
in the menu options.

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:13.710
And it's nice that it gives you
that quick jump to the tool you need

00:26:13.710 --> 00:26:15.400
to be able to fix the items.

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:17.860
So when I talk about a
wizard, it's something

00:26:17.860 --> 00:26:22.500
that does a few shortcuts for you for
what you obviously need help with.

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:27.680
And I call them wizards
because it's a dark art

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:32.490
sometimes reading my mind,
but it seems to manage quite well.

00:26:32.490 --> 00:26:34.500
So it must be magical.

00:26:34.500 --> 00:26:39.130
Anyway, so do they assist authors in
checking for accessibility problems?

00:26:39.130 --> 00:26:41.010
Again, an accessibility check.

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:44.650
And do they help with the repairs?

00:26:47.220 --> 00:26:51.360
And do they promote and integrate
their accessibility features?

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:56.290
In other words,
do you have to search for it?

00:26:56.290 --> 00:26:59.930
Do you have to really look for how
to do something, or does it try

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:03.170
to do it for you and
then tell you it's done?

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:10.880
I'm not trying to tell everyone
not to use certain tools at all,

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:14.620
but you'll notice that there
is a hidden agenda to this talk

00:27:14.620 --> 00:27:17.400
because slightly [Inaudible 27:17].

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:21.200
Anyway, make sure that the
authoring tools promote

00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:23.980
and integrate their accessibility
features, but they let you know

00:27:23.980 --> 00:27:28.360
what they're doing, and you
can change it if you need to.

00:27:28.360 --> 00:27:31.500
And again, I take a glance.

00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:37.550
So anyway, so when authoring content,
you need to make it accessible.

00:27:38.730 --> 00:27:39.860
That's a given.

00:27:39.860 --> 00:27:42.520
You've come to this day of
talks where you've had lots

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:46.110
of people, passionate,
telling you lots of hints and tips,

00:27:46.110 --> 00:27:49.290
and me with my little soapbox
saying don't use the overlays

00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:50.290
because I'm naughty.

00:27:51.870 --> 00:27:54.730
But you need to make
sure it's accessible.

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:55.440
It's on you.

00:27:55.440 --> 00:27:57.110
No one else can take that from you.

00:27:57.110 --> 00:28:01.690
You can have someone audit it and
tell you what to do, but it's you.

00:28:01.690 --> 00:28:03.690
You are the one
creating the content.

00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:08.860
So it's quite a big responsibility
because then you get less sarcasm

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:12.550
from me, if I happen to know you.

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:16.890
Anyway, ATAG helps, because it
helps you work out what to focus on.

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:18.820
It's got some guidelines.

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:22.720
Some can be slightly misinterpreted,
like with the automatic processes,

00:28:22.720 --> 00:28:27.140
but it does let you know
what you need to focus on.

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:30.490
Can I make the
changes, am I helped?

00:28:30.490 --> 00:28:34.260
It's not about leaving you to try
and work out what to do on your own.

00:28:36.660 --> 00:28:40.548
And it's often best
used with this checklist

00:28:40.549 --> 00:28:44.170
before doing any WCAG testing
that's done on your website.

00:28:44.170 --> 00:28:47.810
Because if you are aware
of the of how to fix items

00:28:47.810 --> 00:28:51.810
and you have gone through it,
If you've done the ATAG part

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:57.230
of making sure your plugins
let you change items, then

00:28:57.230 --> 00:29:01.950
when you come to do a check on
your website that you've authored,

00:29:01.950 --> 00:29:04.930
I'm assuming it's a website
that you document or whatever...

00:29:04.930 --> 00:29:07.740
But if you've done the ATAG
part, and made sure

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:11.890
you've applied all these items
to the content you're offering,

00:29:11.890 --> 00:29:14.582
then when you come to do an audit,

00:29:14.583 --> 00:29:17.750
the items found will
be the edge cases

00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:21.300
and not the... I don’t know,
another alt tag of logo

00:29:21.300 --> 00:29:23.850
when it's not even a logo.

00:29:25.190 --> 00:29:27.420
And if the plugins or
things do not allow you

00:29:27.420 --> 00:29:30.790
to create accessible content,
others are available.

00:29:30.790 --> 00:29:33.620
They are like search engines,
there's always others available.

00:29:33.620 --> 00:29:37.370
And if there isn't one that suits
your needs, ask the community,

00:29:37.370 --> 00:29:45.370
because I'm sure that they
will be able to advise you

00:29:45.410 --> 00:29:48.220
on what they recommend,
including Joe,

00:29:48.220 --> 00:29:49.860
who might have
authored one himself.

00:29:51.290 --> 00:29:53.010
Anyway, questions?

00:29:56.196 --> 00:29:58.170
 <v Joost> We do have
a question lined up,

00:29:58.170 --> 00:30:01.270
and I actually have some
questions too, but let's start

00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:04.010
with a question from
Yohann in Sales.

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:06.600
I'm assuming he's Dutch,
I'm not butchering his name.

00:30:08.480 --> 00:30:13.760
This AI or machine learning,
can it now do accessibility for us?

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:15.250
Will we get to that point?

00:30:15.250 --> 00:30:21.650
If you stop screen sharing,
we can see you a bit better.

00:30:21.650 --> 00:30:23.970
 <v Helen> Are you sure you want to?

00:30:23.970 --> 00:30:24.740
I don't know.

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:26.740
 <v Joost> Yes, I'm sure.

00:30:26.740 --> 00:30:30.960
 <v Helen> But anyway, AI,
I do think I should chat

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:32.390
to Chris Land about that one.

00:30:32.390 --> 00:30:38.210
But when it comes to AI,
it's getting there, but it's only

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:40.060
as clever as the people
that programme it.

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:45.670
I know that when Facebook
first introduced AI for images,

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:49.270
I'd post a photo of my son
with a knight's helmet on,

00:30:49.270 --> 00:30:54.060
and the alternative text computed
would be person, indoors,

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:55.620
maybe wearing shoes.

00:30:55.620 --> 00:30:57.180
And I'm like, hang
on, there's a helmet?

00:30:57.180 --> 00:30:57.860
What?

00:30:57.860 --> 00:31:03.600
And I do find that
when it comes to AI,

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:10.910
it can be incredibly intelligent,
but it's gaining this knowledge

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:12.290
from what we're telling it.

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:15.660
So if we're not putting
meaningful alternative text

00:31:15.660 --> 00:31:20.760
when it gets it wrong,
it's not going to be able to learn.

00:31:20.760 --> 00:31:24.180
So obviously,
I'm always correcting AI,

00:31:24.180 --> 00:31:28.650
because my son is always wearing
shoes... well, sometimes he doesn't.

00:31:28.650 --> 00:31:30.190
Oh dear, yes, anyway.

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:34.910
But maybe wearing shoes did get
me because I did wonder, like,

00:31:34.910 --> 00:31:38.500
how much is the AI being trained
by people obsessed with shoes.

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:48.460
But when using alternative text,
I do think that when we amend it,

00:31:48.460 --> 00:31:51.040
and when there's AI involved,
I know that Facebook quite often

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:53.870
will sell my data back to
whatever machines are learning

00:31:53.870 --> 00:31:56.460
in the background because we all
know they're there to make money.

00:31:57.650 --> 00:32:00.090
You get something for free,
so they've got to make money

00:32:00.090 --> 00:32:01.400
out of you somehow.

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:05.090
I sound so dark there.

00:32:05.090 --> 00:32:10.660
But anyway, when it comes to AI,
yes, it could do accessibility

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:12.280
for you to a point.

00:32:14.020 --> 00:32:18.940
And this is where we have to
be able to edit ourselves.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:21.910
This is why I find the
overlays dangerous.

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:25.830
Because they are using a form of
AI where they inject JavaScript

00:32:25.830 --> 00:32:29.040
into your site and sometimes
make it less accessible

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:32.770
in the first place because
of what they've added in.

00:32:32.770 --> 00:32:35.390
And they make it so that
you don't edit it yourself.

00:32:39.320 --> 00:32:40.390
How is that helping anyone?

00:32:40.390 --> 00:32:44.600
How are they learning from
the mistakes they make?

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:48.342
True AI will make
suggestions and then learn

00:32:48.343 --> 00:32:50.670
from the feedback you give.

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:56.090
I know that because Christopher
Land does do a lot of talks on AI,

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:59.930
and he's very
entertaining with them.

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:03.870
And one of the things I've noticed
is when he's talking about it,

00:33:03.870 --> 00:33:08.080
he does examples of Dall-E, where
they do the art from suggestions.

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:15.850
And as a point of, if anyone tells
Dall-E... I forget now, but anyway

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:16.570
 <v Joost> Dall-E.

00:33:16.570 --> 00:33:20.290
 <v Helen> I'm thinking of
Dolly the sheep now, aren't I?

00:33:20.290 --> 00:33:27.440
Yes, anyway, but if everyone told
Dall-E that a car was a plane,

00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:34.380
when it had to do artwork of
a car and it shows a plane,

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:36.580
it's not wrong, it's just
going by what it's been told.

00:33:37.690 --> 00:33:41.090
So if we're not telling the
AI, or we're not nurturing...

00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:44.220
I know someone was saying to me
once that AI is like a toddler,

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:46.800
and as I have a toddler,
I know how it goes.

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:49.860
You have to nurture them so that
they learn right from wrong.

00:33:49.860 --> 00:33:52.910
But you also have to put up
with a lot of temper tantrums,

00:33:52.910 --> 00:33:54.970
and messes along the way.

00:33:54.970 --> 00:33:58.140
It's a learning
process for everyone.

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:06.140
And if we don't teach AI, hopefully
that human life is worth saving...

00:34:06.650 --> 00:34:08.150
just putting it out there.

00:34:08.150 --> 00:34:13.290
But if we don't teach AI
empathy and understanding,

00:34:13.290 --> 00:34:15.540
how will it do accessibility well?

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:23.540
So it's not there yet, but I do
believe it will get there if,

00:34:24.420 --> 00:34:29.250
but only if we help
teach a bit to them.

00:34:29.250 --> 00:34:32.380
And yes, Yohan, it's fun,
isn't it, having children

00:34:32.380 --> 00:34:35.080
that don't like sleeping
at certain times?

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:37.350
 <v Joost> I can tell.

00:34:37.350 --> 00:34:42.400
I've got four kids who are luckily
now slightly older than toddler age,

00:34:42.400 --> 00:34:43.860
so I can actually sleep.

00:34:43.860 --> 00:34:47.200
 <v Helen> Oh, no, then you stay
up wondering where they are

00:34:47.200 --> 00:34:48.390
